Climate change is considered as one of the major threats to global biodiversity in the 21
 st century (
 Walther et al. 2002). Changes in future climatic conditions are predicted to alter the distribution and abundance of species, and coupled with increases in habitat fragmentation may lead to species extinction (
 Brown et al. 1997; 
 Walther et al. 2002; 
 Root et al. 2003; 
 Wake 2007). Species with limited dispersal abilities, small geographic ranges, or confined to specialized habitats are particularly vulnerable to extinction (
 Pounds et al. 1999; 
 Sodhi and Ehrlich 2010). Predictive models suggest that if climate change continues unchecked, 37% of global species might be extinct by the end of 2050 (
 Thomas et al. 2004).
